                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc form="Codex">
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <material key="parchment"/>
                                </support>
                                <extent>
                                    <measure unit="leaf">136</measure>
                                    <measure unit="quire">13</measure>
                                    <measure unit="leaf" type="blank">
                                        <locus from="1r" to="4r">Fols 1r–4r, </locus>
                                        <locus from="134r" to="136v">134r–136v</locus>
                                    </measure>
                                    <dimensions type="outer" unit="mm">
                                        <height>305</height>
                                        <width>210</width>
                                        <depth>62</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                    <note>The boards are 8 mm thick and cut to the size of the bookblock.</note>
                                </extent>

                              <collation>
                                <signatures>Decorated quire marks on the central upper margin of the quires.</signatures>
                                <list>
                                  <item xml:id="q1">
                                    <dim unit="leaf">4</dim>
                                    <locus from="1" to="4">Fols 1–4</locus>
                                  </item>
                                  <item xml:id="q2">
                                    <dim unit="leaf">10</dim>
                                    <locus from="5" to="14">Fols 5–14</locus>
                                  </item>
                                  
                                  <item xml:id="q13">
                                    <dim unit="leaf">12</dim>
                                    <locus from="125" to="136">Fols 125–136</locus>
                                  </item>
                                </list>
                              </collation>


                                <condition key="good">
                                  The chain-stitches on the spine of the first and second sewing station are broken in some points.
                                  The attachment between the lower board and the third and fourth sewing station is weak.
                                  The parchment is not well scraped because remains of tissues and hairs are present.
                                  Tears occurred during the manufacture are repaired using a thread of vegetal origin.
                                </condition>

                            </supportDesc>

                            <layoutDesc>
                              <layout columns="2" writtenLines="27">
                                <note>Data on dimension are taken from <locus target="#46r">fol. 46r</locus>.</note>
                                <locus from="5r" to="133v">Fols 5r–133v</locus>
                                <dimensions unit="mm">
                                  <height>205</height>
                                  <width>164</width>
                                </dimensions>
                                <dimensions type="margin">
                                  <dim type="top">30</dim>
                                  <dim type="bottom">69</dim>
                                  <dim type="right">28</dim>
                                  <dim type="left">15</dim>
                                  <dim type="intercolumn"/>
                                </dimensions>
                                <ab type="ruling" subtype="pattern">1-1-11/0/0/C</ab>
                                <ab type="pricking" subtype="pattern">
                                  The layout corresponds to the pattern I defined by D. Nosnitsin: the text is written above the first ruled line, the vertical and horizontal pricks are visible
                                  and they are located in the margins.
                                  On the lower margin of the bifolio fols. 47 - 52 is ruled an horizontal line, which probably indicated where the parchment had to be cut, in order to obtain the the bifolio.
                                  In other cases the perimeter is traced using a blue crayon or a pencil (fols. 107v, 108r).
                                </ab>
                              </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>

                        <handDesc>
                          <handNote script="Ethiopic" xml:id="h1">
                            <seg type="ink">Black, red</seg>
                          </handNote>
                        </handDesc>

                        <decoDesc>
                            <decoNote type="punctuation" xml:id="d2">
                              <locus target="#24ra">Fol. 24ra</locus>
                              <desc>The texts are separeted by a band of black and red dots.
                              </desc>
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="frame" xml:id="d3">
                              <locus from="1v" to="4v">Fols 1v–4v, </locus>
                              <locus from="134r" to="136r">134r–136r</locus>
                              <desc>Simple frame traced in pencil.
                              </desc>
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote type="drawing" xml:id="d4">
                              <locus target="#22v #29v">Fols. 22v, 29v</locus>
                              <desc>Floral motif in pencil.
                              </desc>
                            </decoNote>
                        </decoDesc>

                        <bindingDesc>
                          <binding contemporary="true" xml:id="binding">
                            <decoNote xml:id="b1">
                              Ethiopic bookbindig with plain wooden boards.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b2" type="bindingMaterial">
                           <material key="wood"/>
                        </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b3" type="Boards">
                              Dark brown wooden boards with marked black irregular grain. The signs of the tool used for carving are clearly visible.
                              There is a split in the thickness of the lower board due to an error occurred during the manufacture.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b6" type="SewingStations">4</decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b7">
                              The sewing is a chain-stitch on four sewing stations (two pairs). The sewing pattern is variation of the <term key="patternA3" ana="#patternA3">pattern A3</term> defined by G. Bozzacchi.
                              Two threads of <term key="animalThread" ana="#animalThread">animal origin</term> have been used. The sewing probably starts from the centrefold of the first quire, it binds the boards and
                              enters in the second quire, continuing the sewing. The ends of the threads are knotted in the centrefold of the last quire.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b9" type="Spine">
                              Small holes are present close to the head and tail of the quires, prabably remains of the tackets.
                            </decoNote>
                            <decoNote xml:id="b11" type="EndLeaves">
                              The first quire has a protective function.
                            </decoNote>
                          </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                      </physDesc>

